éliès, and Oskar Schlemmer revolutionized not only images but also everything surrounding them: the screen, the darkness, and the experience of bodies and space. At the heart of the book is “the black screen,” a technology of darkness that spawned today’s blue and green screens and has undergirded numerous advanced art and film practices to this day. Turning familiar art and film narratives on their heads, Artificial Darkness is a revolutionary treatment of an elusive, yet fundamental, aspect of art and media history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArt, ModernxHistoryx20th century. 0aArt, Moderny20th centuryxHistory. 0aArt, Modern. 0aShades and shadows in artxHistory. 0aShades and shadows in art. 7aART / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226329024423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226329024.jpg  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles